<br>
I have a general sense that things aren't really gel'ing yet though. There's a couple of reasons I feel this way that I will share, which I don't intend like criticism, although it might sound like it.<br>
<br>
Item 1. Communication and Direction<br>
<br>
It's difficult to separate these two issues, since poor communication can hide the fact that there really is good direction, but it's just not apparent to the members. I'd like to everyone use the boards more to improve communication. The board address should probably be included in the MoTD, since it looks like it's not getting much traffic. Guild chat only addresses people online at a particular time, which tends to be a relatively small fraction of players interested in any particular news.<br>
<br>
Some things that need to be communicated on a regular basis:<br>
<br>
a. What are the guilds current priorities? Cleric epic? PoP flags? 51+ spells? <br>
<br>
b. What raids are being planned? When are they happening? How do the support the guilds priorities.<br>
<br>
c. What has happened? If I haven't been able to log in for awhile, I'd like to know the significant accomplishments -- such-and-so raid went down and someone picked up an epic piece, nice item, necessary spell etc.<br>
<br>
d. Recruitment activities, leaving/new officers.<br>
<br>
e. Anything else that helps me to plan my precious entertainment hours, so I can concern myself with playing my character to the best of my abilities, and not just waiting to see if something is going to happen.<br>
<br>
Item 2. Raid Planning<br>
<br>
Again, I thought the Maiden's Raid was well planned, well executed. The Sebilis raid, was set up (as far as I could tell) the day before, without a mention on the raid board that it was happening. The potential CoM raid was setup a couple of days ahead of time, but didn't have a specific day or time or mention of it on the raid board. I don't think I'm perfect, the one event I set up had one time mentioned in the title and a different time mentioned in the body of the message. The point though, is to try and give people the best information you can so they can plan.<br>
<br>
There's a nice 'sample raid' posted on the board, some things that also help in raid planning:<br>
<br>
    a. Specific date and time posted on the raid board, several days before hand.<br>
    b. classes/levels required, levels/classes permitted.<br>
    c. Meeting location<br>
    d. Specific go/no-go criteria (e.g. the raid won't happen if we don't have 2 enchanters and a 56+cleric by 8:00pm EST)<br>
    e. Late arrivals tolerated?<br>
    f. Loot policy<br>
    g. Chat channel to be used for orgainising the raid (should generally not be the guild channel)<br>
<br>
These are all about setting expectations, so any discussion can happen ahead of time on the boards, and not bog the whole raid down by having discussions in game.<br>
<br>
Item 3: Guild Chat<br>
<br>
Pure and simple, what guild chat should be is subjective and probably different to some extent for everyone. I think Faelawen has some guidelines listed somewhere.<br>
<br>
Things to keep in mind:<br>
<br>
     a. Are you speaking to help someone, to get help, or to brag/hear yourself talk? <br>
     b. Do 15 other people really care about what I have to say?<br>
     c. Will a tell to someone suffice, or does everyone need to know about this?<br>
     d. Can I solve the problem on my own before asking for help? eg. Ask for a port/rez/price check/loc etc. from the zone or friend first, before asking the guild.<br>
     e. Is what I'm saying about what I need or what I can do to help the guild?<br>
<br>
Some particular pet peeves. This is the stuff that bugs me, I'm not saying there's something wrong with the people who do these things, it's just that I view them as unnecessary and a waste of my time every time I read them in guild chat.<br>
<br>
      a. Any argument -- take it to tells<br>
      b. Price check on a &lt;...&gt;<br>
      c. Is this &lt;no-drop item&gt; used for anything? Yes it is, look it up on Allakhazam's. (Exception for items found in the first couple of weeks after a release)<br>
      d. Any rant that takes more than one message to convey.<br>
      e. Any blow-by-blow of events that you aren't personally involved in or not of great general interest to the majority of people online.<br>
<br>
That said, I don't like rules governing the chat. I would like people to be respectful of the others online, and strive to make their communication valuable to the guild. Hopefully, this will provoke some discussion.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading.<br>
